Joshua Smith Final Project CMSC320

This project investigates the hard to define concept of beauty in facial images. Instead of throwing a convolutional neural net at the problem and aiming for an accurate detector, we aim to make human-understandable observations on what might make someone be considered "more attractive". In order to do this, we will be reading in a dataset consisting of 5500 portraits, their corresponding beauty score on a scale of 1-5, and a set of facial keypoints for each portrait. We aim to make observations upon the relation between these facial keypoints and perceived attractiveness. I predict that there will be some slight correlations, but that the majority of what constitutes beauty will not be captured in only facial shape. In the paper linked below, where this dataset was derived from, a deep learning method on the input images was capable of achieving a pierson coefficient (r) of about 0.8. This will not be a benchmark we aim for however, because we are exploring a different explanatory variable. While deep learning methods are effective in terms of performance, they are hardly interpretable in terms of human logic, so it is hard to have any take-aways from the study.

Now we need to download our dataset. This is the SCUT-FBP5500 dataset documented here: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1511.02459.pdf

The download link is here: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1w0TorBfTIqbquQVd6k3h_77ypnrvfGwf/view Once the zip is downloaded, unzip and place the 7 items in the data folder created above. This dataset was the result of a facial attractiveness study where pictures of people were presented to 60 raters, who rated the beauty of the portrait on a scale of 1-5. The dataset also contains pictures of the people, and locations of facial keypoints in each image - what we will be using. Evidently, the data read in worked correctly as the attributes matched with the corresponding image. Looking at the variety of the images, we can see that they were taken with slightly different distances away from the camera and with different tilts. Because of this, the facial keypoints provided by the dataset will not be an objective measure of the persons face structure, so we will have to look at relative pose measures to create traits that could potentially inform us about the person. without scaling via ratios, if we were to look at pixel inter-pupillary distance, somebody with wide eyes farther from the camera may have the same ipd value as someone with close eyes who was pictured closer to the camera. First, we will need to read in the facial keypoints data provided in .pts files. This was done by reading in each file according to the participant id, then unpacking it into is 172 length points vector, which was reshaped to by 86x2 vector representing 86 points.

In [7]:
import struct
pt_list = []
index = 0
for i, row in data.iterrows():
    pt_fn = './data/facial landmark/' + row['id'] + '.pts'
    pts_data = open(pt_fn, encoding="ISO-8859-1").read()
    if len(pts_data) == 692: #not all point files are complete, dont include those ones
        points = struct.unpack('i172f', bytes(pts_data, "ISO-8859-1"))
        new_pts = []
        for g in range(len(points)//2):
            new_pts.append([points[1 + (2*g)], points[2 + (2*g)]])
        data.loc[i, "pt_i"] = int(index)
        index += 1
    pt_list.append(new_pts)
    
pts = np.array(pt_list)

def get_dist(p1, p2):
    return np.sqrt(((p1[0] - p2[0])*(p1[0] - p2[0])) + ((p1[1] - p2[1])*(p1[1] - p2[1])))

for i, row in data.iterrows():
    index = data['pt_i'][i]
    if not (index >= 0):
        continue
    points = pts[int(index)]
    data.loc[i, "face_width"] = np.max(points[:,0]) - np.min(points[:,0])
    data.loc[i, "face_height"] = np.max(points[:,1]) - np.min(points[:,1])
    data.loc[i, "eye_width"] = get_dist(points[58], points[59])
    data.loc[i, "eye_height"] = get_dist(points[11], (points[58] + points[59])/2)
    data.loc[i, "lip_height"] = get_dist(points[11], points[76])
    data.loc[i, "lip_width"] = get_dist(points[79], points[73])
    data.loc[i, "nose_width"] = get_dist(points[68], points[64])
    data.loc[i, "nose_height"] = get_dist(points[11], points[66])
    
        #next we will get the ratios for all of the values, because objective pixel value depend on photo zoom/external factors
    data.loc[i, "face_r"] = data['face_width'][i] / data['face_height'][i]
    data.loc[i, "eye_width_r"] = data['eye_width'][i] / data['face_width'][i]
    data.loc[i, "eye_height_r"] = data['eye_height'][i] / data['face_height'][i]
    data.loc[i, "lip_width_r"] = data['lip_width'][i] / data['face_width'][i]
    data.loc[i, "lip_height_r"] = data['lip_height'][i] / data['face_height'][i]
    data.loc[i, "nose_width_r"] = data['nose_width'][i] / data['face_width'][i]
    data.loc[i, "nose_height_r"] = data['nose_height'][i] / data['face_height'][i]

As mentioned before, raw pixel values will be effected by the pose and orientation of the person in the photo. In order to make standardized values, we can compute ratios of face distances in relation to overall head width or height. For example, if a person's inter-pupilary distance is half of their head width, this value will not change significantly whether they are far or close from the camera. Specifically, I computed the ratio between face width and face height, the ratio between eye width and face width, the ratio between how high the eyes are placed and face height, the ratio between lip width and face width, the ratio between lip height and face height, the ratio between nose width and face width, and finally the ratio between nose height and face height.

Evidently, we found some significant correlations between facial structure attributes and perceived attractiveness. The width of someones nose, when standardized by face width, has a negative correlation corresponding to a decrease of 0.45 in beauty score for every 0.1 increase in nose to face width ratio. Lip width did not have a significant correlation with the beauty score. Lip height (distance from chin) had a negative correlation with beauty score, suggesting that a smaller chin is considered more attractive in general. The overall head width/height ratio had a weak regression suggesting that having a skinnier head is slightly more attractive, but not as significant as other factors previously studied. Now lets make a multi-linear regression

from sklearn import linear_model
clf = linear_model.LinearRegression()
d = np.array(data[["face_width", "face_height", "eye_width", "eye_height", "lip_width", "lip_height", "nose_width", "nose_height", "face_r", "eye_width_r", "eye_height_r", "lip_width_r", "lip_height_r", "nose_width_r", "nose_height_r"]])
y = np.array(data['rating'])
clf.fit(d,y)
print(clf.coef_)
print(clf.intercept_)
print(clf.score(d,np.array(data['rating'])))
pred = clf.predict(d)
mse = np.sum((np.array(data['rating']) - pred)*(np.array(data['rating']) - pred))/len(d)
print("mse: {}".format(mse))

Adding these encodings did help slightly! Now the R^2 is .128, meaning that 12.8% of variation can be explained by our predictor, which is pretty good for real world data on something as qualitative as perceived beauty. Given that there are at most 17 trainable parameters in the above 2 models, we haven't had to worry about overfitting on a >5000 points dataset. I implemented other models including a fully connected neural net in pytorch, but accuracy did not exceed that of the multi-linear fit so either my fcn implementation was flawed (I spent many hours attempting to debug it) or the linear regression was simply a better solution for the classification problem.

Conclusions:

To summarize, we read in the dataset data and formatted it into a pandas dataframe. Then we did some exploratory analysis on the data, viewing histograms of beauty ratings. Then, we designed our own features based on facial keypoints, distances between them, and relative ratios. This gave us a means of comparing the people in our dataset objectively according to facial structure ratios. We did a variety of single variate fits to find which attributes correlated with beauty score. Interestingly, having a skinny nose and a small chin (low lip height) were found to be the most effective qualities in improving beauty score. Finally, we did 2 multi-linear fits on the data, which allowed us to achieve .12 r^2 on the beauty score. This means that by simply knowing the positions of keypoints on somebody's face, we can predict 12% of the beauty score reliably, with the other 88% not being captured by the linear fit. However, considering we used facial keypoints and not actual images, the majority of information that dictates qualitative "beauty" were withheld, so I was happy with a 0.12 r^2. Overall, this study revealed correlations with perceived facial beauty that I was unaware of, but certainly find interesting. While some might criticise trying to automate the detection of something that is in "the eye of the beholder" this study does investigate an important issue. Physical looks are an extremely impactful force in every aspect of our lives, even in places where it shouldn't be, like a professional workplace. Studies have shown attractive people are perceived as more intelligent, trustworthy, and are more upwardly mobile in the workplace. Therefore, attempting to formally understand what constitutes "beauty" has its merits.
